CANDLE syndrome is an extremely rare
genetic condition characterized by follicular hyperkeratosis
and leukopenia. It is caused by mutations in the UNC13D gene

which encodes a protein involved in the fusion of granules within immune cells. Symptoms of CANDLE syndrome typically appear in the first few months of life and include a distinctive follicular hyperkeratosis
dry skin rash. Other symptoms may include fever
and leukopenia. CANDLE syndrome is diagnosed based on a combination of clinical features and genetic testing. There is currently no cure for CANDLE syndrome
but treatment is focused on managing the symptoms and preventing complications.
